In this work, co-crystals of progesterone with 2-chloro-4-nitroaniline, 2,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid,
-biphenol were synthesized by slow evaporation and with a molar ratio of 1:1. The crystal
structures have been presented and discussed in detail in this paper. Speciﬁcally, CNA and DHB,
which present similar molecule conﬁgurations, showa rather diverse hydrogen bonding network when
they co-crystallize with PROG. Both CNA and DHB work as a powerful “tra

The linear shape of the DOD molecule generates a broader connectivity pattern that, to some extent,
may help in the prediction of the crystal
co-crystal structure. Additionally, all the co-crystal structures
were conﬁrmed by powder X-ray di
raction spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy, and di
calorimetry. The dissolution tests indicate that faster rates and higher concentrations of PROG were
attained after the co-crystallization, especially for PROG-CNA. This might be attributable to more
stable and abundant interactions which are composed of multiple C-H
interactions between CNAand PROG. In the long term, the investigation of crystal structures provides
positive support for the selection of suitable co-formers using the crystal engineering strategies.
H.Z. and J.X. carried out all the experiments; J.Q., Z.Z., and D.X. wrote the manuscript;
and X.W., L.H., and M.M. supervised the research and revised the manuscript.
